### About
In cooperation with the [Network-Linked Data Index](https://cida.usgs.gov/nldi/about) project, the navigation services were developed to provide network connectivity for the [StreamStats](https://streamstats.usgs.gov) application via [RESTful](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Representational_state_transfer) web services. This API is intended to document the available service endpoints and provide limited example usage to assist developers in building outside programs that leverage the same data sources in an effort to minimize duplicative efforts across the USGS and other agencies.   

### Status
The Navigation Services project currently provides three navigation options (flow path, network path, and network trace) for navigating the national NHDplus v2 medium resolution datasets. 

These resources can be found by selecting the [Available Navigation Resources](./#/Navigation/GET/AvailableNavigationResources) option.
* Flow path (also known as raindrop path) navigation
  *  Provides the ability to leverage a custom flow direction algorithm optimized for the selected network datasets to trace downstream using the flow direction grid and NHD network to determine the flow path of a raindrop for any given location. 
* Network path navigation
  * Requires two locations and leverages the NHD network to identify if these locations are related by a downstream tributary or other type of network. 
* Network trace navigation 
  * Provides the ability to search either upstream or downstream for a specified source data type such as gage, bridge, or water quality sampling location. 

### Getting Started
The Navigation Services performs multiple procedures which include; database and geospatial queries, service requests, and spatial operations to compile and create simple response and hypermedia links to other related resources. The responses can be directly consumed by custom client applications and be used to more fully decouple the server and client. The following figure describes the intended client services relationship. Where client/server calls are iterative and response hypermedia can be used to guide the client actions to the related resource. 

<img alt="NavigationOverview.jpg" 
src="data:image/png;base64," />

For example, after the initial request, the available Navigation resources endpoint provides a list of all navigation resources available, with corresponding links to the `rel: "self by id"` relationship tag indicating the link will take the user to additional information, such as the configuration object required to execute the route procedure, which provides the network route given the client provided configuration properties (see [Navigation Resource Feature Route](./#/Navigation/UNSPECIFIED/NavigationResourceFeatureRoute) for more information).

### Using the API
The URL and sample can be obtained by accessing one of the following resources located on the sidebar (or selecting the menu button located on the bottom of the screen, if viewing on a mobile device).  
<img alt="sidebarScreenshot.jpg" 
src="data:image/jpeg;base64," />


The sidebar displays the available resources with accompanying HTTP method and associated URL. Selecting a resource URL will open the resources documentation page which includes a resource definition, method description, sample url and additional method information such as;

* The description of the resource
* The Service URL.
* URL Parameters (if any).
  * Parameter Name,
  * Value Type,
  * A description of what the parameter represents,
  * Whether the parameter is required or optional,
  * And an example input parameter.
* A REST Query URL test tool that builds an example url, based on the given input parameter values.
* And an example response from the query.

### Content-Types
The content type supported by each resource is `application/json`. It is set as the default content type but can be set via the HTTP header.

### Common Status Codes
Common HTTP status codes returned by the services

| Code &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;   |When     
| ------- |---------
| `200`   | Status  `OK`.
| `400`   | Status `Bad Request`. When the request data cannot be read.
| `404`   | Status `Not Found`. When resource is not available.
| `500`   | Status `Internal Server Error`. Please contact the administrator. 

### Example
Web service request can be performed using most HTTP client libraries. The following illustrated a typical http request/response performed by a client application.

```
GET /navigationservices/navigation HTTP/1.1
Host: streamstats.usgs.gov
Accept: application/json

```
